  "prompt": "Why is big G used in the formula of force?",
  "response": "Big G, denoted as \\( G \\), is used in the formula for the gravitational force to represent the **universal gravitational constant**. It is a proportionality constant that appears in **Newton's law of universal gravitation**, which describes the force of attraction between two masses.\n\nThe formula for the gravitational force is:\n\n\\[\nF = G \\frac{m_1 m_2}{r^2}\n\\]\n\nHere\u2019s why \\( G \\) is used:\n\n1. **Proportionality**: Newton's law states that the gravitational force \\( F \\) is directly proportional to the product of the two masses (\\( m_1 \\) and \\( m_2 \\)) and inversely proportional to the square of the distance (\\( r \\)) between them. To convert this proportionality into an equation, a constant (\\( G \\)) is needed.\n\n2. **Universal Constant**: \\( G \\) is a fundamental constant of nature that quantifies the strength of the gravitational force. Its value is the same everywhere in the universe and is experimentally determined.\n\n3. **Units**: \\( G \\) ensures that the units of the equation work out correctly. In the SI system, \\( G \\) has units of \\( \\text{m}^3 \\text{kg}^{-1} \\text{s}^{-2} \\), which balances the equation and gives the force in newtons (N).\n\nWithout \\( G \\), the equation would only express a proportional relationship and would not have the correct physical dimensions or numerical value. Thus, \\( G \\) is essential for accurately calculating the gravitational force.",
